this project.

00:19:40.860 --> 00:19:43.200
What was it about the
script and the project

00:19:43.200 --> 00:19:44.559
that really appealed to you?

00:19:44.559 --> 00:19:46.600
AVA DUVERNAY: Well, thank
you all for being here.

00:19:46.600 --> 00:19:49.018
Really, really happy to see you.

00:19:49.018 --> 00:19:53.310
And one thing I want to say
about the women in the book

00:19:53.310 --> 00:19:58.500
and in our film is that
Gugu Mbatha-Raw does not

00:19:58.500 --> 00:19:59.940
play just her mother.

00:19:59.940 --> 00:20:02.160
She's an astrophysicist.

00:20:02.160 --> 00:20:05.250
She's Dr. Kate Murry, which
is really important because we

00:20:05.250 --> 00:20:07.770
want to make sure that we know
that girls can participate

00:20:07.770 --> 00:20:08.780
in STEM.

00:20:08.780 --> 00:20:12.030
That's important in medicine,
education, math, science,

00:20:12.030 --> 00:20:13.150
all that good stuff.

00:20:13.150 --> 00:20:15.240
So we want to make
sure we point that out.

00:20:15.240 --> 00:20:18.530
Don't ask her to do any math
problems here on the stage,

00:20:18.530 --> 00:20:21.050
but she does them in the movie.

00:20:21.050 --> 00:20:23.730
But, yeah, it was really cool
to get a call from Disney.

00:20:23.730 --> 00:20:25.830
Because sometimes in
Hollywood, Hollywood

00:20:25.830 --> 00:20:28.500
likes you to ask
for permission, just

00:20:28.500 --> 00:20:31.140
like a lot of people in life
want girls and women to ask

00:20:31.140 --> 00:20:33.410
for permission to do things.

00:20:33.410 --> 00:20:39.320
They want us to
sometimes pinch ourselves

00:20:39.320 --> 00:20:45.370
and sometimes to prove that
you're worth doing something.

00:20:45.370 --> 00:20:47.340
And so we find that in
a lot of places in life.

00:20:47.340 --> 00:20:49.340
But now and then, you get
a beautiful experience

00:20:49.340 --> 00:20:52.310
when people welcome you in,
and they love you just the way

00:20:52.310 --> 00:20:52.810
you are.

00:20:52.810 --> 00:20:54.810
And that's what happened
to me at Disney.

00:20:54.810 --> 00:20:57.510
They called me, and they
said, we love your work,

00:20:57.510 --> 00:20:59.730
we love your voice, and
we want you to just come

00:20:59.730 --> 00:21:01.039
in and be who you are.

00:21:01.039 --> 00:21:02.580
And those are the
kind of experiences

00:21:02.580 --> 00:21:03.520
you want to embrace.

00:21:03.520 --> 00:21:05.880
Those are the kind of people
you want to align yourself with,

00:21:05.880 --> 00:21:07.470
and those are the
kind of people that we

00:21:07.470 --> 00:21:09.720
were able to make "A Wrinkle
in Time" with at Disney.

00:21:09.720 --> 00:21:11.511
EILEEN NAUGHTON: That's
a remarkable story.

00:21:11.511 --> 00:21:14.697
You did not pick up a camera
to direct until you were 33.

00:21:14.697 --> 00:21:15.905
AVA DUVERNAY: Now that's old.

00:21:15.905 --> 00:21:18.005
Well, all of the
kids know that's old.

00:21:18.005 --> 00:21:19.796
EILEEN NAUGHTON: It's
very young, actually.

00:21:19.796 --> 00:21:22.320
AVA DUVERNAY: It's
older for directors

00:21:22.320 --> 00:21:27.250
because most directors start
20, 21, in their early 20s.

00:21:27.250 --> 00:21:31.890
So to start in your
30s, it's unusual.

00:21:31.890 --> 00:21:33.390
EILEEN NAUGHTON:
So advice would you

00:21:33.390 --> 00:21:35.580
give women, and
particularly young girls,

00:21:35.580 --> 00:21:38.280
about following their
dreams, their tropisms

00:21:38.280 --> 00:21:39.840
and having courage?

00:21:39.840 --> 00:21:41.520
AVA DUVERNAY: It's
really just, what

00:21:41.520 --> 00:21:44.910
you're doing now does not
have to be what you always do.

00:21:44.910 --> 00:21:48.250
Who you are right now is not
who you're always going to be.

00:21:48.250 --> 00:21:50.760
And just know that
there are steps to take.

00:21:50.760 --> 00:21:53.400
There are other paths
to follow, to explore.

00:21:53.400 --> 00:21:55.500
But don't feel
stuck in one place.

00:21:55.500 --> 00:21:56.700
Embrace where you are now.

00:21:56.700 --> 00:21:59.250
Learn what you can from it,
but also stay open to the fact

00:21:59.250 --> 00:22:01.290
that there are other
things that you can do.

00:22:01.290 --> 00:22:04.200
A lot of people talk
about me and my journey

00:22:04.200 --> 00:22:08.400
in terms of race and gender, but
part of my story is also age.

00:22:08.400 --> 00:22:11.370
Because in the industry that I'm
in, I got a start quite late.

00:22:11.370 --> 00:22:13.680
And it's just proof that
nothing is impossible.

00:22:13.680 --> 00:22:14.605
It really isn't.

00:22:14.605 --> 00:22:16.230
EILEEN NAUGHTON:
Nothing is impossible,

00:22:16.230 --> 00:22:17.590
ladies and gentlemen.

00:22:17.590 --> 00:22:18.090
OK.

