00:27:42.680 --> 00:27:45.210
in a number of women's
advocacy organizations,

00:27:45.210 --> 00:27:47.360
so for that, we thank you.

00:27:47.360 --> 00:27:49.920
I understand you read this book
when you were a young girl.

00:27:49.920 --> 00:27:53.700
And how did you feel that
Ava's film enhances the story

00:27:53.700 --> 00:27:56.690
and makes it more
relevant to the world

00:27:56.690 --> 00:27:59.815
that we're living today
and experiencing today?

00:27:59.815 --> 00:28:01.190
REESE WITHERSPOON:
Well, the book

00:28:01.190 --> 00:28:03.020
was written quite a while ago.

00:28:03.020 --> 00:28:04.900
I think Ava did an
extraordinary job.

00:28:04.900 --> 00:28:07.670
I read this book when I
was 12, and I loved it.

00:28:07.670 --> 00:28:10.230
And I think primarily because
I loved science fiction,

00:28:10.230 --> 00:28:11.771
and I hadn't read
a lot of books that

00:28:11.771 --> 00:28:13.890
had a girl at the center of it.

00:28:13.890 --> 00:28:15.800
So I thought I was
Meg Murry and I

00:28:15.800 --> 00:28:19.670
was going to travel through the
universe and do amazing things.

00:28:19.670 --> 00:28:21.210
And I loved all of
that, and then I

00:28:21.210 --> 00:28:22.460
read every book in the series.

00:28:22.460 --> 00:28:24.720
So I was just
completely obsessed.

00:28:24.720 --> 00:28:28.650
And so when Ava called me to
be in it, I was so excited.

00:28:28.650 --> 00:28:31.250
I didn't know who
I would play either

00:28:31.250 --> 00:28:35.600
because the misseses are all
billions and billions of years

00:28:35.600 --> 00:28:37.700
old.

00:28:37.700 --> 00:28:41.680
My son said, what does she
want you to play, an old lady?

00:28:41.680 --> 00:28:44.510
But she, of course, had
this beautiful vision

00:28:44.510 --> 00:28:52.790
of making them timeless and
celestial and intergalactic.

00:28:52.790 --> 00:28:56.600
And they have these qualities
that are the qualities

00:28:56.600 --> 00:28:59.930
that you'd want to have three
incredible women guide you

00:28:59.930 --> 00:29:03.530
through the universe,
wisdom, a sense of fun,

00:29:03.530 --> 00:29:05.060
and a sense of past.

00:29:05.060 --> 00:29:07.100
And I just think
it was beautiful,

00:29:07.100 --> 00:29:08.515
the way she imagined it.

00:29:08.515 --> 00:29:09.890
EILEEN NAUGHTON:
And you have one

00:29:09.890 --> 00:29:11.900
of the most beautiful
transformations

00:29:11.900 --> 00:29:17.650
from a somewhat human form into
this mystical flying creature.

00:29:17.650 --> 00:29:20.930
It was one of the most
exciting scenes in the movie.

00:29:20.930 --> 00:29:24.080
Can we talk a little bit
about the special effects

00:29:24.080 --> 00:29:26.780
and the challenge
in creating a movie

00:29:26.780 --> 00:29:30.350
like that, that so heavily
relies on technology, really,

00:29:30.350 --> 00:29:32.930
to produce these effects?

00:29:32.930 --> 00:29:34.460
AVA DUVERNAY: Yeah,
no, I think it

00:29:34.460 --> 00:29:37.160
was a beautiful team
that worked on the film

00:29:37.160 --> 00:29:38.640
and the special effects with me.

00:29:38.640 --> 00:29:40.550
Our visual effects
supervisor, Rich McBride,

00:29:40.550 --> 00:29:42.200
also a great woman
over at Disney

00:29:42.200 --> 00:29:43.850
who heads up special
effects there,

00:29:43.850 --> 00:29:46.460
Mimi Steele, another
woman Tamara Kent.

00:29:46.460 --> 00:29:49.760
So a lot of women on
our visual effects team.

00:29:49.760 --> 00:29:52.010
But I think the actress
that was most impacted

00:29:52.010 --> 00:29:56.630
by the visual effects was Storm
Reid because Storm Reid, as Meg

00:29:56.630 --> 00:29:57.680
Murry, gets to fly.

00:29:57.680 --> 00:29:59.054
And that's one of
the reasons why

00:29:59.054 --> 00:30:01.220
I wanted to make this
movie, to see a girl fly,

00:30:01.220 --> 00:30:04.310
hop planets, save the
world from the darkness,

00:30:04.310 --> 00:30:05.980
and do all these amazing things.

00:30:05.980 --> 00:30:09.290
But Storm actually, you
know, put her in a harness,

00:30:09.290 --> 00:30:12.137
hiked her up in the air, and
she had to fly through the air.

00:30:12.137 --> 00:30:13.220
It looked like it was fun.

00:30:13.220 --> 00:30:14.755
STORM REID: It was fun.

00:30:14.755 --> 00:30:16.380
EILEEN NAUGHTON: And
it was believable.

00:30:16.380 --> 00:30:17.130
You did it believably.

00:30:17.130 --> 00:30:18.046
STORM REID: Thank you.

00:30:18.046 --> 00:30:20.840
I had some challenges, and
it was a learning curve

00:30:20.840 --> 00:30:24.980
with the stunts and the special
effects and green screen

00:30:24.980 --> 00:30:27.190
all working together.

00:30:27.190 --> 00:30:30.030
It was a challenge, but Miss
Ava was right there in my corner

00:30:30.030 --> 00:30:32.870
and helping me and showing me
previs, which is basically,

00:30:32.870 --> 00:30:35.840
the animation of what's
going to be in the film.

00:30:35.840 --> 00:30:36.980
So she helped a lot.

00:30:36.980 --> 00:30:40.430
And it was still
hard because you

00:30:40.430 --> 00:30:42.680
have to imagine the
unimaginable, which

00:30:42.680 --> 00:30:43.460
is really hard.

00:30:43.460 --> 00:30:44.750
But it came together.

00:30:44.750 --> 00:30:46.356
AVA DUVERNAY: So
there was one scene--

00:30:46.356 --> 00:30:48.034
STORM REID: No,
don't rat me out.

00:30:48.034 --> 00:30:48.950
AVA DUVERNAY: I'm not.

00:30:48.950 --> 00:30:49.834
I'm not.

00:30:49.834 --> 00:30:52.250
She did a really good job, and
you'll see it in the movie.

00:30:52.250 --> 00:30:55.880
But there was one scene
where I said, OK, Storm,

00:30:55.880 --> 00:30:59.360
here in this place, you're
standing here in a field.

00:30:59.360 --> 00:31:02.120
A tree is going to pop up
fully grown from the ground.

00:31:02.120 --> 00:31:04.010
And she's like, OK.

00:31:04.010 --> 00:31:06.020
And I said, so can
you imagine that?

00:31:06.020 --> 00:31:10.050
But she's an actress so she
goes through her feelings.

00:31:10.050 --> 00:31:12.920
So she's never experienced
a tree popping up

00:31:12.920 --> 00:31:14.180
from the ground, fully grown.

00:31:14.180 --> 00:31:17.060
So she was like, so it's
going to just pop up

00:31:17.060 --> 00:31:20.360
like pop up from the ground
or on top of the ground.

00:31:20.360 --> 00:31:22.550
I said, no, from the ground,
Storm, from the ground.

00:31:22.550 --> 00:31:23.680
So it took an--

00:31:23.680 --> 00:31:24.930
STORM REID: It took some time.

00:31:24.930 --> 00:31:27.310
AVA DUVERNAY: --intellectual
approach to it.

00:31:27.310 --> 00:31:30.200
But those are the kinds
of fantastic spaces

00:31:30.200 --> 00:31:31.500
that she found herself in.

00:31:31.500 --> 00:31:33.800
And she was 13 years
old when she did it.

00:31:33.800 --> 00:31:35.570
So when you watch
the movie, imagine

00:31:35.570 --> 00:31:38.690
this 13-year-old
actress, brilliant girl,

00:31:38.690 --> 00:31:40.800
doing all of these
amazing things.

00:31:40.800 --> 00:31:42.685
She's the real
warrior of our movie.

00:31:42.685 --> 00:31:42.990
STORM REID: Thank you.

00:31:42.990 --> 00:31:43.280
AVA DUVERNAY: Truly.

00:31:43.280 --> 00:31:44.696
EILEEN NAUGHTON:
I love it, Storm.

00:31:44.696 --> 00:31:46.142
[APPLAUSE]

00:31:46.142 --> 00:31:49.430
Storm, Meg is a
beloved character

00:31:49.430 --> 00:31:55.370
and a brave and determined
girl, a physics whiz.

00:31:55.370 --> 00:31:59.900
You've mentioned that you really
saw yourself in that character.

00:31:59.900 --> 00:32:02.240
What was it about Meg?

00:32:02.240 --> 00:32:03.470
STORM REID: Yes.

00:32:03.470 --> 00:32:05.900
Well, when I was reading
"A Wrinkle in Time"

00:32:05.900 --> 00:32:09.020
in the sixth grade,
I didn't see myself

00:32:09.020 --> 00:32:11.780
as being Meg because she
wasn't written that way.

00:32:11.780 --> 00:32:14.240
And I'm a very visual
person so if I'm

00:32:14.240 --> 00:32:17.180
reading something and something
is written a way, then

00:32:17.180 --> 00:32:17.990
that's how it is.

00:32:17.990 --> 00:32:20.390
And I could love it, and I did.

00:32:20.390 --> 00:32:23.550
But once I got the script and
Miss Ava sent it over to me,

00:32:23.550 --> 00:32:25.450
I felt like it just all clicked.

00:32:25.450 --> 00:32:27.560
And it made sense,
and it made sense

00:32:27.560 --> 00:32:30.650
for a girl at the
center of the universe

00:32:30.650 --> 00:32:33.020
to be African-American
to represent

00:32:33.020 --> 00:32:35.375
African-American girls
and just girls in general.

00:32:35.375 --> 00:32:37.970
[APPLAUSE]

00:32:37.970 --> 00:32:41.180
Yes, and just represent
girls in general.

00:32:41.180 --> 00:32:44.750
And then, going into Meg,
I feel like everybody

00:32:44.750 --> 00:32:48.000
can find a little piece
of Meg in themselves.

00:32:48.000 --> 00:32:51.770
And I feel like Meg is very
determined and strong-willed,

00:32:51.770 --> 00:32:53.160
and I feel like
I'm the same way.

00:32:53.160 --> 00:32:57.610
So I feel like personally, we
kind of are on the same level.

00:32:57.610 --> 00:33:00.770
And I feel like as girls and
as just teenagers growing up

00:33:00.770 --> 00:33:02.720
in this dark world,
we're just trying

00:33:02.720 --> 00:33:05.420
to grow up and find ourselves
and surround ourselves

00:33:05.420 --> 00:33:07.070
by good people.

00:33:07.070 --> 00:33:09.230
And sometimes, we have
challenges and mistakes

00:33:09.230 --> 00:33:10.716
and faults on top of that.

00:33:10.716 --> 00:33:12.340
So that's what we're
all going through.

00:33:12.340 --> 00:33:13.610
EILEEN NAUGHTON: Well,
we're just human, Storm.

00:33:13.610 --> 00:33:14.450
We love it.

00:33:14.450 --> 00:33:16.575
OPRAH WINFREY: I think it's
important to note, too,

00:33:16.575 --> 00:33:19.460
that Ava fought to get this Meg.

00:33:19.460 --> 00:33:20.930
She fought to get Storm.

00:33:20.930 --> 00:33:22.178
Will you tell that story?

00:33:22.178 --> 00:33:22.886
AVA DUVERNAY: Oh.

00:33:22.886 --> 00:33:24.290
[LAUGHTER]

00:33:24.290 --> 00:33:26.534
EILEEN NAUGHTON: Oprah is
channeling her inner Oprah

00:33:26.534 --> 00:33:27.515
right now.

00:33:27.515 --> 00:33:29.390
AVA DUVERNAY: Well,
there were a lot of girls

00:33:29.390 --> 00:33:31.223
all over the world who
auditioned to be Meg.

00:33:31.223 --> 00:33:34.730
And you're looking for
that special girl who

00:33:34.730 --> 00:33:38.580
encompasses everything that
this beautiful character has

00:33:38.580 --> 00:33:41.540
symbolized for so many decades,
since the book was published

00:33:41.540 --> 00:33:43.490
in 1963.

00:33:43.490 --> 00:33:46.201
And so you're looking
for the one girl.

00:33:46.201 --> 00:33:48.200
And so out of the hundreds
of girls that we saw,

00:33:48.200 --> 00:33:51.420
Storm Reid was the one
who was meant to be Meg.

00:33:51.420 --> 00:33:56.450
And I think it really speaks
to, everyone has their place.

00:33:56.450 --> 00:34:00.450
Everyone has somewhere or some
place that they're meant to be,

00:34:00.450 --> 00:34:02.990
someone in the world
that you're meant

00:34:02.990 --> 00:34:06.110
to be connected with in
your family, something

00:34:06.110 --> 00:34:08.480
that you're supposed
to be in your classroom

00:34:08.480 --> 00:34:10.690
or in your life,
if you're an adult.

00:34:10.690 --> 00:34:16.079
And once you align with
that place, it just clicks.

00:34:16.079 --> 00:34:17.120
And that's what happened.

00:34:17.120 --> 00:34:19.310
Storm was not just
in the right place

00:34:19.310 --> 00:34:21.179
at the right time,
her whole life,

00:34:21.179 --> 00:34:24.139
she was moving towards
being in that audition room

00:34:24.139 --> 00:34:26.330
and being ready to be Meg.

00:34:26.330 --> 00:34:30.260
All of the little steps that
brought her to be in the place,

00:34:30.260 --> 00:34:33.800
in the time, in the
space to fulfill

00:34:33.800 --> 00:34:36.920
and be something important to
someone else, and that was me.

00:34:36.920 --> 00:34:39.350
And so whether you're an
actress and it's your time

00:34:39.350 --> 00:34:41.870
to be in a movie,
which is a rare thing,

00:34:41.870 --> 00:34:44.570
or whether it's your
opportunity to be someone

00:34:44.570 --> 00:34:46.850
important to someone
in your life,

00:34:46.850 --> 00:34:50.449
you have to cultivate
yourself each and every day.

00:34:50.449 --> 00:34:52.790
So that when the
opportunity comes

00:34:52.790 --> 00:34:54.949
to really stand up
and step up and be

00:34:54.949 --> 00:34:58.100
someone important to someone,
that you're ready to do that.

00:34:58.100 --> 00:34:59.010
And Storm did that.

00:34:59.010 --> 00:35:01.730
So when it was her
time and I met her,

00:35:01.730 --> 00:35:04.170
she was ready to be
someone important to me

00:35:04.170 --> 00:35:06.780
and to be someone who
carries this whole movie.

00:35:06.780 --> 00:35:12.170
So I think her journey
can speak to anyone,

00:35:12.170 --> 00:35:15.620
in terms of prepare every day in
your life to be a great person

00:35:15.620 --> 00:35:17.540
so that when the moment
of greatness arises,

00:35:17.540 --> 00:35:18.638
you're ready for it.

00:35:18.638 --> 00:35:19.763
EILEEN NAUGHTON: Beautiful.

00:35:19.763 --> 00:35:21.695
[APPLAUSE]

00:35:21.695 --> 00:35:27.190
Now, Gugu, you play Dr.
Kate Murry, Meg's mother

00:35:27.190 --> 00:35:29.410
and a scientist and
an equal partner

00:35:29.410 --> 00:35:32.830
to your wild scientist
physicist husband.

00:35:32.830 --> 00:35:34.000
What did that feel like?

00:35:34.000 --> 00:35:36.250
And rumor is that you
got to hang out at NASA.

00:35:36.250 --> 00:35:37.104
Is that true?

00:35:37.104 --> 00:35:38.020
GUGU MBATHA-RAW: Yeah.

00:35:38.020 --> 00:35:40.190
Well, it was a
real honor for me.

00:35:40.190 --> 00:35:44.531
I think getting to work with
Ava, who I've admired for such

00:35:44.531 --> 00:35:46.780
a long time, getting to play
a scientist, as you said,

00:35:46.780 --> 00:35:50.020
in the book, she's often
described as Mrs. Murry.

00:35:50.020 --> 00:35:53.050
And the idea that we have
Dr. Kate, that she's not just

00:35:53.050 --> 00:35:58.480
defined by her marriage, that
is an equal partner to Dr. Alex

00:35:58.480 --> 00:36:00.150
Murry, played by Chris Pine.

00:36:00.150 --> 00:36:04.030
And for me, it was really
fascinating to kind of cling

00:36:04.030 --> 00:36:07.000
onto this idea that he's
been away for four years.

00:36:07.000 --> 00:36:08.800
What this marriage
and this family

00:36:08.800 --> 00:36:11.950
is based on is
obviously love, but also

00:36:11.950 --> 00:36:14.020
this intellectual
meeting of minds,

00:36:14.020 --> 00:36:18.324
that she's really found her
partner in life who is--

00:36:18.324 --> 00:36:19.990
we sort of talked
about them like a sort

00:36:19.990 --> 00:36:21.730
of power couple of science.

00:36:21.730 --> 00:36:23.740
You know, that they
would do these TED Talks,

00:36:23.740 --> 00:36:26.050
that they were
sort of like this--

00:36:26.050 --> 00:36:28.660
I don't know, that their
connection was intellectual

00:36:28.660 --> 00:36:31.330
and not just love and family.

00:36:31.330 --> 00:36:32.980
And that's what
really kept her going

00:36:32.980 --> 00:36:35.140
and kept her trying
to figure out

00:36:35.140 --> 00:36:37.370
where he was in that long time.

00:36:37.370 --> 00:36:39.730
So yes, we did get
to go and visit

00:36:39.730 --> 00:36:43.060
JPL in Pasadena,
which was fascinating.

00:36:43.060 --> 00:36:45.570
Getting to meet
real-- have you been?

00:36:45.570 --> 00:36:47.530
So I saw heads go, yes.

00:36:47.530 --> 00:36:49.270
Getting to meet real
scientists, people

00:36:49.270 --> 00:36:53.690
who are really planning missions
to Mars, it was so interesting.

00:36:53.690 --> 00:36:58.660
We also met this wonderful
doctor, Dr. Stephon Alexander,

00:36:58.660 --> 00:37:01.690
who wrote this book called,
"The Jazz of Physics",

00:37:01.690 --> 00:37:04.000
and he sort of
correlated the link

00:37:04.000 --> 00:37:06.460
between the work
of John Coltrane

00:37:06.460 --> 00:37:10.130
the saxophonist and
science and physics.

00:37:10.130 --> 00:37:12.580
And I mean, it was
mind blowing to me,

00:37:12.580 --> 00:37:16.310
and I can't pretend that I
have retained all of it now.

00:37:16.310 --> 00:37:18.910
AVA DUVERNAY: We'll give
you a pop quiz on equations.

00:37:18.910 --> 00:37:19.550
GUGU MBATHA-RAW:
But it was great.

00:37:19.550 --> 00:37:22.240
And the fact that Ava had him
as the consultant on the movie,

00:37:22.240 --> 00:37:24.617
to be able to introduce us
to that world of science,

00:37:24.617 --> 00:37:25.450
is really inspiring.

00:37:25.450 --> 00:37:26.380
EILEEN NAUGHTON: What
a rich experience

00:37:26.380 --> 00:37:28.150
for you all and for us all.

00:37:28.150 --> 00:37:30.790
You know, Time Magazine notes,
in its review of the movie,

00:37:30.790 --> 00:37:33.340
that the book and
movie is about what

00:37:33.340 --> 00:37:37.180
it means to be a source of light
in a world in which darkness

00:37:37.180 --> 00:37:39.010
seems only to proliferate.

00:37:39.010 --> 00:37:43.510
Oprah, you have a beautiful
line in the movie about darkness

00:37:43.510 --> 00:37:44.650
being stronger than light.

00:37:44.650 --> 00:37:46.400
Can you talk to us a
little bit about that

00:37:46.400 --> 00:37:47.980
because several of
you have already

00:37:47.980 --> 00:37:50.540
mentioned darkness in
the world, and this

00:37:50.540 --> 00:37:51.760
is such an inspiring film.

00:37:51.760 --> 00:37:53.468
OPRAH WINFREY: What
I think is incredible

00:37:53.468 --> 00:37:56.650
is that when Madeleine
L'Engle wrote it in 1962,

00:37:56.650 --> 00:37:59.350
she was talking about
the Cold War and all

00:37:59.350 --> 00:38:06.400
of the experiences of
that day and Civil Rights

00:38:06.400 --> 00:38:12.370
Movement and everything
that people were facing.

00:38:12.370 --> 00:38:13.900
And what I know is
that you're never

00:38:13.900 --> 00:38:16.207
going to run out of
darkness, as you're not

00:38:16.207 --> 00:38:17.290
going to run out of light.

00:38:17.290 --> 00:38:19.660
Because this is
the planet Earth,

00:38:19.660 --> 00:38:24.610
and we are the planet of yin
and yang, of darkness and light,

00:38:24.610 --> 00:38:25.690
of opposites.

00:38:25.690 --> 00:38:28.960
And so the darkness,
which Mrs. Which says

00:38:28.960 --> 00:38:33.160
is spreading so fast
these days, the only thing

00:38:33.160 --> 00:38:35.650
faster than light
is the darkness.

00:38:35.650 --> 00:38:38.980
And so you need
warriors of the light

00:38:38.980 --> 00:38:41.921
to help banish the darkness.

00:38:41.921 --> 00:38:44.170
If you think about it, if
we turned all the lights off

00:38:44.170 --> 00:38:48.550
in this room, and you were
only holding a small candle,

00:38:48.550 --> 00:38:50.380
that candle would
light up the darkness.

00:38:50.380 --> 00:38:52.390
It would help to
banish the darkness.

00:38:52.390 --> 00:38:55.210
It only takes a little
bit of your light

00:38:55.210 --> 00:38:56.470
to banish the darkness.

00:38:56.470 --> 00:39:00.040
It takes a lot of darkness
to overcome the light.

00:39:00.040 --> 00:39:02.510
But just a little
flicker from you.

00:39:02.510 --> 00:39:06.340
And so, wherever there is
confusion, wherever there's

00:39:06.340 --> 00:39:09.160
jealousy, as Mrs. Which
talks about and is

00:39:09.160 --> 00:39:12.880
able to show everyone in the
movie what that darkness looks

00:39:12.880 --> 00:39:15.130
like, where it shows
up in your life,

00:39:15.130 --> 00:39:18.010
just a little bit
of your light helps

00:39:18.010 --> 00:39:20.500
to dissipate and destroy that.

00:39:20.500 --> 00:39:22.810
So I think it's
about these times,

00:39:22.810 --> 00:39:26.110
and all times are about
you reaching for the light

00:39:26.110 --> 00:39:27.460
inside yourself.

00:39:27.460 --> 00:39:30.070
And that's the real
work of your life,

00:39:30.070 --> 00:39:33.490
is to figure out who
you are and how do

00:39:33.490 --> 00:39:38.540
you become more of who you are.

00:39:38.540 --> 00:39:40.330
Not what your
friends are, not even

00:39:40.330 --> 00:39:43.180
what your mother and your father
and everybody wants you to be.

00:39:43.180 --> 00:39:45.190
But this journey,
particularly at this stage

00:39:45.190 --> 00:39:48.820
in your development,
is about, who am I,

00:39:48.820 --> 00:39:51.610
and how do I become
more of that.

00:39:51.610 --> 00:39:53.860
And how do I bring
more of my light.

00:39:53.860 --> 00:39:55.982
First to yourself,
because you've got

00:39:55.982 --> 00:39:57.190
to give it to yourself first.

00:39:57.190 --> 00:40:00.700
You can't give to yourself
what you don't have.

00:40:00.700 --> 00:40:02.440
So you fill yourself up.

00:40:02.440 --> 00:40:04.340
And I used to be so
afraid of people saying,

00:40:04.340 --> 00:40:06.631
oh, she's so full of herself,
she's so full of herself.

00:40:06.631 --> 00:40:09.320
And now, I work on--

00:40:09.320 --> 00:40:10.450
you've heard that before?

00:40:10.450 --> 00:40:12.990
[LAUGHTER]

00:40:12.990 --> 00:40:14.320
Forget those people.

00:40:14.320 --> 00:40:15.910
Those people are
not your friends.

00:40:15.910 --> 00:40:19.990
What you want to work on
is filling yourself up

00:40:19.990 --> 00:40:24.000
with as much light, as much
kindness, as much goodness,

00:40:24.000 --> 00:40:25.050
as much preparation.

00:40:25.050 --> 00:40:27.300
Because that's
what luck is, being

00:40:27.300 --> 00:40:29.814
prepared so when the moment
of opportunity shows up--

00:40:29.814 --> 00:40:31.230
